message:
refactor(runtime): replace Option<T> recv_event return with RecvEvent<T> to distinguish Disconnected vs Cancelled

`recv_event()` previously swallowed the distinction between two
fundamentally different causes of channel termination:

    async fn recv_event<T>(...) -> Option<T> {
        rx.recv(runtime_cx).await.ok()
    }

Both `mpsc::RecvError::Disconnected` (all senders dropped — the
channel is genuinely closed and the receiver loop should exit) and
`mpsc::RecvError::Cancelled` (the runtime context was cancelled
mid-await — the loop should log and exit, but this is a different
shutdown shape from "no more work") collapsed to `None`. That
merging made it impossible for the caller to log cancellation
separately from natural channel close, and it hid the fact that a
cancellation at the recv point leaves the rest of the event
processing pipeline in a potentially half-drained state.

This commit introduces a small purpose-built enum:

    enum RecvEvent<T> {
        Item(T),
        Closed,
        Cancelled,
    }

…and reshapes `recv_event` into:

    async fn recv_event<T>(
        runtime_cx: &RuntimeLoopCx,
        rx: &mut mpsc::Receiver<T>,
    ) -> RecvEvent<T> {
        match rx.recv(runtime_cx).await {
            Ok(value) => RecvEvent::Item(value),
            Err(mpsc::RecvError::Disconnected) => RecvEvent::Closed,
            Err(mpsc::RecvError::Cancelled) => RecvEvent::Cancelled,
        }
    }

The only caller — `ObservationRuntime`'s native event coalescer
loop — is updated to match on the new variants explicitly:

    match runtime_timeout(&loop_cx, flush_wait, recv_event(&loop_cx, &mut event_rx)).await {
        Ok(RecvEvent::Item(event)) => {
            // existing event-processing body, unchanged
        }
        Ok(RecvEvent::Closed) => break,
        Ok(RecvEvent::Cancelled) => {
            debug!("Native event coalescer recv cancelled");
            break;
        }
        Err(_elapsed) => {
            // Timer elapsed; next loop iteration drains due batches.
        }
    }

Two concrete wins:

1. Cancellation now emits a debug log line before exiting the
   loop, so operators running under a dynamic shutdown sequence
   (the case where the runtime cx is cancelled by a higher-level
   orchestrator) can see the specific reason in tracing output
   instead of conflating it with "the sender side of the channel
   dropped naturally".
2. Future handlers that want different behavior for
   Disconnected vs Cancelled — for example, a retry path that
   treats Cancelled as transient but Disconnected as terminal —
   can slot in without further refactoring of the recv signature.

No runtime-observable event ordering change; both termination
paths still break out of the loop exactly as they did before.
The previous `let Some(event) = maybe_event else { break; }` shape
is removed because the new match arms handle each variant directly.

